# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cosmos-network
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] A **Byzantine fault** is a condition of a system, particularly a distributed computing system, where a fault occurs such that different symptoms are presented to different observers, including imperfect information on whether a system component has failed.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is also known as a **Byzantine generals problem**, a **Byzantine agreement problem**, or a **Byzantine failure**.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is any fault presenting different symptoms to different observers.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine failure is the loss of a system service due to a Byzantine fault in systems that require consensus among multiple components.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The Byzantine allegory considers a number of generals who are attacking a fortress.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The generals must decide as a group whether to attack or retreat; some may prefer to attack, while others prefer to retreat.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The important thing is that all generals agree on a common decision, for a half-hearted attack by a few generals would become a rout, and would be worse than either a coordinated attack or a coordinated retreat.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated by the presence of treacherous generals who may not only cast a vote for a suboptimal strategy; they may do so selectively.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] For instance, if nine generals are voting, four of whom support attacking while four others are in favor of retreat, the ninth general may send a vote of retreat to those generals in favor of retreat, and a vote of attack to the rest.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Those who received a retreat vote from the ninth general will retreat, while the rest will attack (which may not go well for the attackers).
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated further by the generals being physically separated and having to send their votes via messengers who may fail to deliver votes or may forge false votes.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Without message signing, Byzantine fault tolerance can only be achieved if the total number of generals is greater than three times the number of disloyal (faulty) generals.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] There can be a default vote value given to missing messages.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] For example, missing messages can be given a "null" value.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Further, if the agreement is that the null votes are in the majority, a pre-assigned default strategy can be used (e.g., retreat).
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The typical mapping of this allegory onto computer systems is that the computers are the generals and their digital communication system links are the messengers.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Although the problem is formulated in the allegory as a decision-making and security problem, in electronics, it cannot be solved by cryptographic digital signatures alone, because failures such as incorrect voltages can propagate through the encryption process.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Thus, a faulty message could be sent such that some recipients detect the message as faulty (bad signature), others see it is having a good signature, and a third group also sees a good signature but with different message contents than the second group.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The problem of obtaining Byzantine consensus was conceived and formalized by Robert Shostak, who dubbed it the *interactive consistency* problem.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] This work was done in 1978 in the context of the NASA-sponsored SIFT project in the Computer Science Lab at SRI International.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] SIFT (for Software Implemented Fault Tolerance) was the brainchild of John Wensley, and was based on the idea of using multiple general-purpose computers that would communicate through pairwise messaging in order to reach a consensus, even if some of the computers were faulty.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] At the beginning of the project, it was not clear how many computers in total were needed to guarantee that a conspiracy of *n* faulty computers could not "thwart" the efforts of the correctly-operating ones to reach consensus.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Shostak showed that a minimum of 3*n+*1 are needed, and devised a two-round 3*n+1* messaging protocol that would work for *n*=1.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] His colleague Marshall Pease generalized the algorithm for any n > 0, proving that 3*n*+1 is both necessary and sufficient.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] These results, together with a later proof by Leslie Lamport of the sufficiency of 3*n* using digital signatures, were published in the seminal paper, *Reaching Agreement in the Presence of Faults.* The authors were awarded the 2005 Edsger W.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] To make the interactive consistency problem easier to understand, Lamport devised a colorful allegory in which a group of army generals formulate a plan for attacking a city.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] In its original version, the story cast the generals as commanders of the Albanian army.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The name was changed, eventually settling on "Byzantine", at the suggestion of Jack Goldberg to future-proof any potential offense-giving.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] This formulation of the problem, together with some additional results, were presented by the same authors in their 1982 paper, "The Byzantine Generals Problem".
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The objective of Byzantine fault tolerance is to be able to defend against failures of system components with or without symptoms that prevent other components of the system from reaching an agreement among themselves, where such an agreement is needed for the correct operation of the system.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The remaining operationally correct components of a Byzantine fault tolerant system will be able to continue providing the system's service as originally intended, assuming there are a sufficient number of accurately-operating components to maintain the service.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] When considering failure propagation only via errors, Byzantine failures are considered the most general and most difficult class of failures among the failure modes.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The so-called fail-stop failure mode occupies the simplest end of the spectrum.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Thus, Byzantine failures can confuse failure detection systems, which makes fault tolerance difficult.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Despite the allegory, a Byzantine failure is not necessarily a security problem involving hostile human interference: it can arise purely from physical or software faults.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] This kind of fault tolerance does not encompass the correctness of the value itself; for example, an adversarial component that deliberately sends an incorrect value, but sends that same value consistently to all components, will not be caught in the Byzantine fault tolerance scheme.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Several early solutions were described by Lamport, Shostak, and Pease in 1982.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] There are many systems that claim BFT without meeting the above minimum requirements (e.g., blockchain).
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Given that there is mathematical proof that this is impossible, these claims need to include a caveat that their definition of BFT strays from the original.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] That is, systems such as blockchain don't guarantee agreement.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] They use resource-intensive mechanisms that make disagreements impractical to maintain.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Several system architectures were designed c.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] 1980 that implemented Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] These include: Draper's FTMP, Honeywell's MMFCS, and SRI's SIFT.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] In 1999, Miguel Castro and Barbara Liskov introduced the "Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance" (PBFT) algorithm, which provides high-performance Byzantine state machine replication, processing thousands of requests per second with sub-millisecond increases in latency.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] After PBFT, several BFT protocols were introduced to improve its robustness and performance.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] For instance, Q/U, HQ, Zyzzyva, and ABsTRACTs, addressed the performance and cost issues; whereas other protocols, like Aardvark and RBFT, addressed its robustness issues.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, Adapt tried to make use of existing BFT protocols, through switching between them in an adaptive way, to improve system robustness and performance as the underlying conditions change.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, BFT protocols were introduced that leverage trusted components to reduce the number of replicas, e.g., A2M-PBFT-EA and MinBFT.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Recent research addresses the scalability limits of traditional BFT implementations (which often incur $O(n^{2})$ communication complexity) by parallelizing consensus.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] For example, the Cerberus protocol maps data to a large, fixed state space to couple consensus instances with specific transaction sets.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] This allows BFT processes to run independently in parallel, enabling linear scalability relative to the network size.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Several examples of Byzantine failures that have occurred are given in two equivalent journal papers.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] These and other examples are described on the NASA DASHlink web pages.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance mechanisms use components that repeat an incoming message (or just its signature, which can be reduced to just a single bit of information if self-checking pairs are used for nodes) to other recipients of that incoming message.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] All these mechanisms make the assumption that the act of repeating a message blocks the propagation of Byzantine symptoms.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] For systems that have a high degree of safety or security criticality, these assumptions must be proven to be true to an acceptable level of fault coverage.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] When providing proof through testing, one difficulty is creating a sufficiently wide range of signals with Byzantine symptoms.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Such testing will likely require specialized fault injectors.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Byzantine errors were observed infrequently and at irregular points during endurance testing for the newly constructed *Virginia*-class submarine, at least through 2005 (when the issues were publicly reported).
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The Bitcoin network works in parallel to generate a blockchain with proof of work allowing the system to overcome Byzantine failures and reach a coherent global view of the system's state.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Some proof of stake blockchains also use BFT algorithms.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance is a crucial concept in blockchain technology, ensuring that a network can continue to function even when some nodes (participants) fail or act maliciously.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] This tolerance is necessary because blockchains are decentralized systems with no central authority, making it essential to achieve consensus among nodes, even if some try to disrupt the process.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Ensuring that an AI system behaves reliably and as intended, especially in the presence of unexpected faults or adversarial conditions, is a complex challenge.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] By accepting that components may fail, and further that frontier AI models may deceive, Byzantine fault tolerance has been proposed as an approach towards AI safety.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Structuring AI systems as ensembles of AI artifacts or modules that check and balance each other leads to strong assurances that no single errant or deceptive component can easily steer the system into an unsafe state.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] , BFT-based systems are designed to tolerate up to one-third of faulty or malicious nodes without compromising the network's integrity.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] Instead of relying on a central authority, the network's security depends on the ability of honest nodes to outnumber and outmaneuver malicious ones.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] BFT is especially important in private or permissioned blockchains, where a limited number of known participants need to reach a consensus quickly and securely.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] These networks often use BFT protocols to enhance performance and security.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] For example, SAFEbus can achieve Byzantine fault tolerance within the order of a microsecond of added latency.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The SpaceX Dragon considers Byzantine fault tolerance in its design.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The Ares rocket avionics, now the Space Launch System (SLS), utilizes a triplex with an interstage of accomplish Byzantine resilience.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] The Orion spacecraft utilizes self-checking pairs to detect and mask Byzantine faults.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] In legislatures, civil societies, polls, statistical surveys, and so forth, systems that require a minimum supermajority threshold agreement greater than two-thirds are similar to consensus reflective of Byzantine Fault Tolerant -like characteristics.
[src:cosmos-network/byzantine-fault] By contrast, systems that operate on the sub-supermajority basis of simple majorities or a minority government could be vulnerable to Byzantine fault -like behavior.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] The Cosmos project was initiated in 2014 by Jae Kwon, who developed the Tendermint consensus algorithm.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] Ethan Buchman joined the project in 2015.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] In 2016, they published the white paper *"Cosmos: A Network of Distributed Ledgers"*, which proposed a network of independent blockchains connected through the Inter-Blockchain Communication (IBC) protocol.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] In April 2017, the Interchain Foundation conducted a token sale that raised approximately $17 million.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] The foundation is legally registered as Interchain Stiftung in the Canton of Zug, supervised by the Swiss Federal Foundation Supervisory Authority (Eidgenossische Stiftungsaufsicht).
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] The Cosmos Hub mainnet was launched on 13 March 2019.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] In 2021, the IBC protocol was introduced, enabling interoperability between independent blockchains.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] (operating as Tendermint Inc.) rebranded to Ignite.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] In February 2023, the Tendermint Core consensus software was forked and renamed CometBFT, maintained as an open-source project.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] The Cosmos stack refers to a set of open-source tools and protocols for building application-specific and interoperable blockchains.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] It includes a modular development framework (Cosmos SDK), a consensus engine (CometBFT), interoperability protocols such as the Inter-Blockchain Communication Protocol (IBC), and support for different execution environments and application-specific modules.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] Extensions to the stack include compatibility layers such as Cosmos EVM, as well as shared security mechanisms such as Interchain Security, which allows blockchains to leverage validator sets from other networks.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] Cosmos uses a proof-of-stake consensus mechanism based on the CometBFT Byzantine Fault Tolerance (BFT) engine, formerly known as Tendermint.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] The academic paper, *"The latest gossip on BFT consensus"* by Buchman, Kwon, and Milosevic (2018), presented the protocol's formal specification.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] A 2025 study provided a universally composable security analysis demonstrating the protocol's resilience against strategic message-delay attacks.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] The Cosmos SDK is framework for building application-specific blockchains and components customization.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] Blockchains built with the Cosmos SDK can interoperate via the IBC protocol, which enables the exchange of data and tokens without a central intermediary.
[src:cosmos-network/cosmos-network] In 2022, decentralized derivatives exchange dYdX announced it would migrate from Ethereum to a dedicated Cosmos-based blockchain, with the new chain launching in October 2023.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Individual coin ownership records are stored in a digital ledger or blockchain, which is a computerized database that uses a consensus mechanism to secure transaction records, control the creation of additional coins, and verify the transfer of coin ownership.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The two most common consensus mechanisms are proof of work and proof of stake.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies are generally viewed as a distinct asset class in practice.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1983, American cryptographer David Chaum conceived of a type of cryptographic electronic money called ecash.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Later, in 1995, he implemented it through Digicash, an early form of cryptographic electronic payments.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Digicash required user software in order to withdraw notes from a bank and designate specific encrypted keys before they could be sent to a recipient.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This allowed the digital currency to be untraceable by a third party.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1996, the National Security Agency published a paper entitled *How to Make a Mint: The Cryptography of Anonymous Electronic Cash*, describing a cryptocurrency system.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The paper was first published in an MIT mailing list (October 1996) and later (April 1997) in *The American Law Review*.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1998, Wei Dai described "b-money," an anonymous, distributed electronic cash system.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Shortly thereafter, Nick Szabo described bit gold.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Like bitcoin and other later cryptocurrencies, bit gold was proposed as a digital currency system in which users would generate money by completing proof-of-work functions whose solutions were cryptographically chained and published.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In January 2009, bitcoin was created by pseudonymous developer Satoshi Nakamoto.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] It used SHA-256, a cryptographic hash function, in its proof-of-work scheme.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In April 2011, Namecoin was created as an attempt at forming a decentralized DNS.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In October 2011, Litecoin was released, which used scrypt as its hash function instead of SHA-256.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Peercoin, created in August 2012, used a hybrid of proof-of-work and proof-of-stake.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency has undergone several periods of growth and retraction, including several bubbles and market crashes, such as in 2011, 2013–2014/15, 2017–2018, and 2021–2023.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In August 2014, the UK announced its Treasury had commissioned a study of cryptocurrencies and what role, if any, they could play in the UK economy.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The study was also to report on whether regulation should be considered.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Its final report was published in 2018, and it issued a consultation on cryptoassets and stablecoins in January 2021.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2021, El Salvador became the first country to accept bitcoin as legal tender, after the Legislative Assembly had voted 62–22 to pass a bill submitted by President Nayib Bukele classifying the cryptocurrency as such.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In August 2021, Cuba followed with Resolution 215 to recognize and regulate cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2021, the government of China, the single largest market for cryptocurrency, declared all cryptocurrency transactions illegal.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This completed a crackdown on cryptocurrency that had previously banned the operation of intermediaries and miners within China.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2022, the world's second largest cryptocurrency at that time, Ethereum, transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an upgrade process known as "the Merge".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] According to the Ethereum Founder, the upgrade would cut both Ethereum's energy use and carbon-dioxide emissions by 99.9%.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On 11 November 2022, FTX Trading Ltd., a cryptocurrency exchange, which also operated a crypto hedge fund, and had been valued at $18 billion, filed for bankruptcy.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] An October 2024 survey from the Pew Research Center found that 63% of adults in the U.S.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] "have little to no confidence that current ways to invest in, trade or use cryptocurrencies are reliable and safe." The survey also reported that 17% of U.S. adults had directly interacted with cryptocurrency, which was statistically unchanged from 2021.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The word "cryptocurrency", in its modern sense, was added to the Oxford English Dictionary in September 2018, with its earliest usage noted as being on Twitter in September 2009; its diminutive, *crypto*, was entered in 2022.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2018 *cryptocurrency* was added to the *Merriam-Webster Dictionary*.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] After the early innovation of bitcoin in 2008 and the early network effect gained by bitcoin, tokens, cryptocurrencies, and other digital assets that were not bitcoin became collectively known during the 2010s as alternative cryptocurrencies, or "**altcoins**".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Sometimes the term "alt coins" was used, or disparagingly, "**shitcoins**".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Paul Vigna of *The Wall Street Journal* described altcoins in 2020 as "alternative versions of Bitcoin" given its role as the model protocol for cryptocurrency designers.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] A Polytechnic University of Catalonia thesis in 2021 used a broader description, including not only alternative versions of bitcoin but every cryptocurrency other than bitcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] As of early 2020, there were more than 5,000 cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Altcoins often have underlying differences when compared to bitcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, Litecoin aims to process a block every 2.5 minutes, rather than bitcoin's 10 minutes which allows Litecoin to confirm transactions faster than bitcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Another example is Ethereum, which has smart contract functionality that allows decentralized applications to be run on its blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Ethereum was the most used blockchain in 2020, according to Bloomberg News.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2016, it had the largest "following" of any altcoin, according to the *New York Times*.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Significant market price rallies across multiple altcoin markets are often referred to as an "altseason".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Stablecoins are cryptocurrencies designed to maintain a stable level of purchasing power.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Notably, these designs are not foolproof, as a number of stablecoins have crashed or lost their peg.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, on 11 May 2022, Terra's stablecoin UST fell from $1 to 26 cents.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The subsequent failure of Terraform Labs resulted in the loss of nearly $40B invested in the Terra and Luna coins.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2022, South Korean prosecutors requested the issuance of an Interpol Red Notice against the company's founder, Do Kwon.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In Hong Kong, the expected regulatory framework for stablecoins in 2023/24 is being shaped and includes a few considerations.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] About 764,000 people who invested after the all time high on 19 January 2025 lost money.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The Melania meme coin experienced extreme volatility in its first days, after which it declined in price.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Memecoins are a category of cryptocurrencies that originated from Internet memes or jokes.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] One example is Dogecoin, a memecoin featuring the Shiba Inu dog from the Doge meme.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Donald Trump and his wife Melania are the subject of their own meme coins, both of which declined in value soon after launch.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Memecoins are known for extreme volatility; for example, the record-high value for a Dogecoin was 73 cents, but that had plunged to 13 cents by mid-2024.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Physical cryptocurrency coins have been made as promotional items and some have become collectibles.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Some of these have a private key embedded in them to access crypto worth a few dollars.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] There have also been attempts to issue bitcoin "bank notes".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The term "physical bitcoin" is used in the finance industry when investment funds that hold crypto purchased from crypto exchanges put their crypto holdings in a specialised bank called a "custodian".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] These physical representations of cryptocurrency do not hold any value by themselves; these are only utilized for collectable purposes.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, the first incarnation of the bitcoin Casascius, coins made of silver, brass or aluminum sometimes with gold plating, or Titan Bitcoin, which in silver or gold versions are sought after by numismatists.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The underlying technical system upon which cryptocurrencies are based was created by Satoshi Nakamoto.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Within a proof-of-work system such as bitcoin, the safety, integrity, and balance of ledgers are maintained by a community of mutually distrustful parties referred to as miners.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners use their computers to help validate and timestamp transactions, adding them to the ledger in accordance with a particular timestamping scheme.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In a proof-of-stake blockchain, transactions are validated by holders of the associated cryptocurrency, sometimes grouped together in stake pools.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called *blocks*, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] A blockchain is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] A "node" is a computer that connects to a cryptocurrency network.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The node supports the cryptocurrency's network through either relaying transactions, validation, or hosting a copy of the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In terms of relaying transactions, each network computer (node) has a copy of the blockchain of the cryptocurrency it supports.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] When a transaction is made, the node creating the transaction broadcasts details of the transaction using encryption to other nodes throughout the node network so that the transaction (and every other transaction) is known.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Node owners are either volunteers, those hosted by the organization or body developing the technology, or those incentivised by rewards from the node network.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove" the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The first timestamping scheme invented was the proof-of-work scheme.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The most widely used proof-of-work schemes are based on SHA-256 and scrypt.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Some other hashing algorithms that are used for proof-of-work include CryptoNote, Blake, SHA-3, and X11.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Another method is called the proof-of-stake scheme.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof-of-stake is a method of securing a cryptocurrency network and achieving distributed consensus through requesting users to show ownership of a certain amount of currency.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] It is different from proof-of-work systems that run difficult hashing algorithms to validate electronic transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The scheme is largely dependent on the coin, and there is currently no standard form of it.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies use a combined proof-of-work and proof-of-stake scheme.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On a blockchain, *mining* is the validation of transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] For this effort, successful miners obtain new cryptocurrency as a reward.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The reward decreases transaction fees by creating a complementary incentive to contribute to the processing power of the network.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The rate of generating hashes, which validate any transaction, has been increased by the use of specialized hardware such as FPGAs and ASICs running complex hashing algorithms like SHA-256 and scrypt.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This arms race for cheaper-yet-efficient machines has existed since bitcoin was introduced in 2009.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Mining is measured by hash rate, typically in TH/s.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] A 2023 IMF working paper found that crypto mining could generate 450 million tons of CO2 emissions by 2027, accounting for 0.7 percent of global emissions, or 1.2 percent of the world total.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] With more people entering the world of virtual currency, generating hashes for validation has become more complex over time, forcing miners to invest increasingly large sums of money to improve computing performance.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Consequently, the reward for finding a hash has diminished and often does not justify the investment in equipment and cooling facilities (to mitigate the heat the equipment produces) and the electricity required to run them.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Popular regions for mining include those with inexpensive electricity, a cold climate, and jurisdictions with clear and conducive regulations.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] By July 2019, bitcoin's electricity consumption was estimated to be approximately 7 gigawatts, around 0.2% of the global total, or equivalent to the energy consumed nationally by Switzerland.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Some miners pool resources, sharing their processing power over a network to split the reward equally, according to the amount of work they contributed to the probability of finding a block.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] A "share" is awarded to members of the mining pool who present a valid partial proof-of-work.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] As of February 2018, the Chinese government has halted trading of virtual currency, banned initial coin offerings, and shut down mining.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Many Chinese miners have since relocated to Canada and Texas.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] One company is operating data centers for mining operations at Canadian oil and gas field sites due to low gas prices.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2018, Hydro Quebec proposed to the provincial government to allocate 500 megawatts of power to crypto companies for mining.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] According to a February 2018 report from *Fortune*, Iceland has become a haven for cryptocurrency miners in part because of its cheap electricity.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2018, the city of Plattsburgh, New York put an 18-month moratorium on all cryptocurrency mining in an effort to preserve natural resources and the "character and direction" of the city.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2021, Kazakhstan became the second-biggest crypto-currency mining country, producing 18.1% of the global exahash rate.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The country built a compound containing 50,000 computers near Ekibastuz.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] An increase in cryptocurrency mining increased the demand for graphics cards (GPU) in 2017.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The computing power of GPUs makes them well-suited to generating hashes.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Popular favorites of cryptocurrency miners, such as Nvidia's GTX 1060 and GTX 1070 graphics cards, as well as AMD's RX 570 and RX 580 GPUs, doubled or tripled in price – or simply went out of stock.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] A GTX 1070 Ti, which was released at a price of $450, sold for as much as $1,100.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Another popular card, the GTX 1060 (6 GB model), released at an MSRP of $250, sold for almost $500.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] RX 570 and RX 580 cards from AMD were out of stock for almost a year.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners regularly buy up the entire stock of new GPUs as soon as they are available.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Nvidia has asked retailers to do what they can when it comes to selling GPUs to gamers instead of miners.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Numerous companies developed dedicated crypto-mining accelerator chips, capable of price-performance far higher than that of CPU or GPU mining.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] At one point, Intel marketed its own brand of crypto accelerator chip, named Blockscale.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] A cryptocurrency wallet is a means of storing the public and private "keys" (address) or seed, which can be used to receive or spend the cryptocurrency.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] With the private key, it is possible to write in the public ledger, effectively spending the associated cryptocurrency.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] With the public key, it is possible for others to send currency to the wallet.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] There exist multiple methods of storing keys or seed in a wallet.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin is pseudonymous, rather than anonymous; the cryptocurrency in a wallet is not tied to a person but rather to one or more specific keys (or "addresses").
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Thereby, bitcoin owners are not immediately identifiable, but all transactions are publicly available in the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Still, cryptocurrency exchanges are often required by law to collect the personal information of their users.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies, such as Monero, Zerocoin, Zerocash, and CryptoNote, implement additional measures to increase privacy, such as by using zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] A recent 2020 study presented different attacks on privacy in cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The attacks demonstrated how the anonymity techniques are not sufficient safeguards.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In order to improve privacy, researchers suggested several different ideas, including new cryptographic schemes and mechanisms for hiding the IP address of the source.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies are used primarily outside banking and governmental institutions and are exchanged over the Internet.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof-of-work cryptocurrencies, such as bitcoin, offer block rewards incentives for miners.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] There has been an implicit belief that whether miners are paid by block rewards or transaction fees does not affect the security of the blockchain, but a study suggests that this may not be the case under certain circumstances.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The rewards paid to miners increase the supply of the cryptocurrency.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] By making sure that verifying transactions is a costly business, the integrity of the network can be preserved as long as benevolent nodes control a majority of computing power.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The verification algorithm requires a lot of processing power, and thus electricity, in order to make verification costly enough to accurately validate the public blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners have to factor in the costs associated with expensive equipment necessary to stand a chance of solving a hash problem, and consider the significant amount of electrical power in search of the solution.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Generally, the block rewards outweigh electricity and equipment costs, but this may not always be the case.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The current value, not the long-term value, of the cryptocurrency supports the reward scheme to incentivize miners to engage in costly mining activities.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2018, bitcoin's design caused a 1.4% welfare loss compared to an efficient cash system, while a cash system with 2% money growth has a minor 0.003% welfare cost.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The main source for this inefficiency is the large mining cost, which is estimated to be US$360 million per year.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This translates into users being willing to accept a cash system with an inflation rate of 230% before being better off using bitcoin as a means of payment.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] However, the efficiency of the bitcoin system can be significantly improved by optimizing the rate of coin creation and minimizing transaction fees.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Another potential improvement is to eliminate inefficient mining activities by changing the consensus protocol altogether.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Transaction fees (sometimes also referred to as *miner fees* or *gas fees*) for cryptocurrency depend mainly on the supply of network capacity at the time, versus the demand from the currency holder for a faster transaction.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The ability for the holder to be allowed to set the fee manually often depends on the wallet software used, and central exchanges for cryptocurrency (CEX) usually do not allow the customer to set a custom transaction fee for the transaction.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Their wallet software, such as Coinbase Wallet, however, might support adjusting the fee.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Select cryptocurrency exchanges have offered to let the user choose between different presets of transaction fee values during the currency conversion.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] One of those exchanges, namely **LiteBit**, previously headquartered in the Netherlands, was forced to cease all operations in August 2023, "due to market changes and regulatory pressure".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The "recommended fee" suggested by the network will often depend on the time of day (due to depending on network load).
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] For Ethereum, transaction fees differ by computational complexity, bandwidth use, and storage needs, while bitcoin transaction fees differ by transaction size and whether the transaction uses SegWit.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In February 2023, the median transaction fee for Ether corresponded to $2.2845, while for bitcoin it corresponded to $0.659.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies have no transaction fees, the most well-known example being Nano (XNO), and instead rely on client-side proof-of-work as the transaction prioritization and anti-spam mechanism.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency exchanges allow customers to trade cryptocurrencies for other assets, such as conventional fiat money, or to trade between different digital currencies.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Crypto marketplaces do not guarantee that an investor is completing a purchase or trade at the optimal price.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] As a result, as of 2020, it was possible to arbitrage to find the difference in price across several markets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Atomic swaps are a mechanism where one cryptocurrency can be exchanged directly for another cryptocurrency without the need for a trusted third party, such as an exchange.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Jordan Kelley, founder of Robocoin, launched the first bitcoin ATM in the United States in February 2014.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The kiosk installed in Austin, Texas, is similar to bank ATMs but has scanners to read government-issued identification such as a driver's license, or a passport to confirm users' identities.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] An initial coin offering (ICO) is a controversial means of raising funds for a new cryptocurrency venture.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] An ICO may be used by startups with the intention of avoiding regulation.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In an ICO campaign, a percentage of the cryptocurrency (usually in the form of "tokens") is sold to early backers of the project in exchange for legal tender or other cryptocurrencies, often bitcoin or Ether.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] According to PricewaterhouseCoopers, four of the 10 biggest proposed initial coin offerings have used Switzerland as a base, where they are frequently registered as non-profit foundations.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The market capitalization of a cryptocurrency is calculated by multiplying the price by the number of coins in circulation.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The total cryptocurrency market cap has historically been dominated by bitcoin accounting for at least 50% of the market cap value where altcoins have increased and decreased in market cap value in relation to bitcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin's value is largely determined by speculation among other technological limiting factors known as blockchain rewards coded into the architecture technology of bitcoin itself.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The cryptocurrency market cap follows a trend known as the "halving", which is when the block rewards received from bitcoin are halved due to technological mandated limited factors instilled into bitcoin which in turn limits the supply of bitcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] As the date reaches near of a halving (twice thus far historically) the cryptocurrency market cap increases, followed by a downtrend.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] By June 2021, cryptocurrency had begun to be offered by some wealth managers in the US for 401(k)s.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency prices are much more volatile than established financial assets such as stocks.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, over one week in May 2022, bitcoin lost 20% of its value and Ethereum lost 26%, while Solana and Cardano lost 41% and 35% respectively.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The falls were attributed to warnings about inflation.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] By comparison, in the same week, the Nasdaq tech stock index fell 7.6 per cent and the FTSE 100 was 3.6 per cent down.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In the longer term, of the 10 leading cryptocurrencies identified by the total value of coins in circulation in January 2018, only four (bitcoin, Ethereum, Cardano and Ripple (XRP)) were still in that position in early 2022.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The total value of all cryptocurrencies was $2 trillion at the end of 2021, but had halved nine months later.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The *Wall Street Journal* has commented that the crypto sector has become "intertwined" with the rest of the capital markets and "sensitive to the same forces that drive tech stocks and other risk assets," such as inflation forecasts.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] There are also *centralized* databases, outside of blockchains, that store crypto market data.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Compared to the blockchain, databases perform fast as there is no verification process.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Four of the most popular cryptocurrency market databases are CoinMarketCap, CoinGecko, BraveNewCoin, and Cryptocompare.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] According to Alan Feuer of *The New York Times*, libertarians and anarcho-capitalists were attracted to the philosophical idea behind bitcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Early bitcoin supporter Roger Ver said: "At first, almost everyone who got involved did so for philosophical reasons.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] We saw bitcoin as a great idea, as a way to separate money from the state." Economist Paul Krugman argues that cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are "something of a cult" based in "paranoid fantasies" of government power.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] David Golumbia says that the ideas influencing bitcoin advocates emerge from right-wing extremist movements such as the Liberty Lobby and the John Birch Society and their anti-Central Bank rhetoric, or, more recently, Ron Paul and Tea Party-style libertarianism.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Steve Bannon, who owns a "good stake" in bitcoin, sees cryptocurrency as a form of disruptive populism, taking control back from central authorities.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin's founder, Satoshi Nakamoto, supported the idea that cryptocurrencies go well with libertarianism.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] "It's very attractive to the libertarian viewpoint if we can explain it properly," Nakamoto said in 2008.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Monthly cryptocurrency transfers under $10,000 to and from Africa reached $316 million in June 2020, according to Chainalysis data.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Reuters reported that bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies are unregulated in many countries and their legal status is unclear, meaning there is no safety net and little recourse for lost funds.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Some migrants in the United Arab Emirates used cryptocurrencies to send remittances home, claiming lower fees compared with traditional remittance services.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2025, some publicly traded companies announced plans to raise capital to buy and hold bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies as treasury assets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Reuters reported that the inherent volatility of crypto tokens makes them a poor fit for boards with a low risk appetite, potentially limiting their appeal beyond core industry players.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The rise in the popularity of cryptocurrencies and their adoption by financial institutions has led some governments to assess whether regulation is needed to protect users.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) has defined cryptocurrency-related services as "virtual asset service providers" (VASPs) and recommended that they be regulated with the same money laundering (AML) and know your customer (KYC) requirements as financial institutions.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In May 2020, the Joint Working Group on interVASP Messaging Standards published "IVMS 101", a universal common language for communication of required originator and beneficiary information between VASPs.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The FATF and financial regulators were informed as the data model was developed.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2020, FATF updated its guidance to include the "Travel Rule" for cryptocurrencies, a measure which mandates that VASPs obtain, hold, and exchange information about the originators and beneficiaries of virtual asset transfers.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Subsequent standardized protocol specifications recommended using JSON for relaying data between VASPs and identity services.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] As of December 2020, the IVMS 101 data model has yet to be finalized and ratified by the three global standard setting bodies that created it.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The European Commission published a digital finance strategy in September 2020.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This included a draft regulation on Markets in Crypto-Assets (MiCA), which aimed to provide a comprehensive regulatory framework for digital assets in the EU.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2021, the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision proposed that banks that held cryptocurrency assets must set aside capital to cover all potential losses.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] For instance, if a bank were to hold bitcoin worth $2 billion, it would be required to set aside enough capital to cover the entire $2 billion.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This is a more extreme standard than banks are usually held to when it comes to other assets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] However, this is a proposal and not a regulation.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The IMF has sought seeking a coordinated, consistent and comprehensive approach to supervising cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Tobias Adrian, the IMF's financial counsellor and head of its monetary and capital markets department said in a January 2022 interview that "Agreeing global regulations is never quick.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In May 2024, 15 years after the advent of the first blockchain, bitcoin, the US Congress advanced a bill to the full House of Representatives to provide regulatory clarity for digital assets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2017, China banned ICOs to cause abnormal return from cryptocurrency decreasing during announcement window.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The liquidity changes by banning ICOs in China was temporarily negative while the liquidity effect became positive after news.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On 18 May 2021, China banned financial institutions and payment companies from being able to provide cryptocurrency transaction related services.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This led to a sharp fall in the price of the biggest proof of work cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] For instance, bitcoin fell 31%, Ethereum fell 44%, Binance Coin fell 32% and Dogecoin fell 30%.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof of work mining was the next focus, with regulators in popular mining regions citing the use of electricity generated from highly polluting sources such as coal to create bitcoin and Ethereum.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2021, the Chinese government declared all cryptocurrency transactions of any kind illegal, completing its crackdown on cryptocurrency.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The proposed legislation was criticised by Cook Islands Crown Law's deputy solicitor general David Greig, who described it as "flawed" and said that some provisions were "clearly unconstitutional".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The Cook Islands Financial Services Development Authority described Drumcliffe's involvement as a conflict of interest.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Similar criticism was echoed by Auckland University of Technology cryptocurrency specialist and senior lecturer Jeff Nijsse and University of Otago political scientist Professor Robert Patman, who described it as government overreach and described it as inconsistent with international law.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Cook Islands Prime Minister Mark Brown defended the legislation as part of the territory's fight against international cybercrime.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On 9 June 2021, El Salvador announced that it will adopt bitcoin as legal tender, becoming the first country to do so.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] As of 17 January 2025, the European Securities and Markets Authority (ESMA) issued guidance to crypto-asset service providers (CASPs) allowing them to maintain crypto-asset services for non-compliant ARTs and EMTs until the end of March 2025.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The rest of MiCA came into force as of 30 December 2024, covering crypto-assets other than ART and EMT and CASPs.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] MiCA excludes crypto-assets if they qualify as financial instruments according to ESMA guidelines published on 17 December 2024 as well as crypto-assets that are unique and not fungible with other crypto-assets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] At present, India neither prohibits nor allows investment in the cryptocurrency market.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2020, the Supreme Court of India had lifted the ban on cryptocurrency, which was imposed by the Reserve Bank of India.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Since then, an investment in cryptocurrency is considered legitimate, though there is still ambiguity about the issues regarding the extent and payment of tax on the income accrued thereupon and also its regulatory regime.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] But it is being contemplated that the Indian Parliament will soon pass a specific law to either ban or regulate the cryptocurrency market in India.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] He mooted regulating the cryptocurrency market rather than completely banning it.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] He favoured following IMF and FATF guidelines in this regard.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] South Africa, which has seen a large number of scams related to cryptocurrency, is said to be putting a regulatory timeline in place that will produce a regulatory framework.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The largest scam occurred in April 2021, where the two founders of an African-based cryptocurrency exchange called Africrypt, Raees Cajee and Ameer Cajee, disappeared with $3.8 billion worth of bitcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Additionally, Mirror Trading International disappeared with $170 million worth of cryptocurrency in January 2021.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2021, South Korea implemented new legislation to strengthen their oversight of digital assets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This legislation requires all digital asset managers, providers and exchanges to be registered with the Korea Financial Intelligence Unit in order to operate in South Korea.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Registering with this unit requires that all exchanges are certified by the Information Security Management System and that they ensure all customers have real name bank accounts.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] It also requires that the CEO and board members of the exchanges have not been convicted of any crimes and that the exchange holds sufficient levels of deposit insurance to cover losses arising from hacks.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Switzerland was one of the first countries to implement the FATF's Travel Rule.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] FINMA, the Swiss regulator, issued its own guidance to VASPs in 2019.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The guidance followed the FATF's Recommendation 16, with stricter requirements.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] According to FINMA's requirements, VASPs need to verify the identity of the beneficiary of the transfer.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In April 2021, the Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey banned the use of cryptocurrencies and cryptoassets for making purchases on the grounds that the use of cryptocurrencies for such payments poses significant transaction risks.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In the United Kingdom, as of 10 January 2021, all cryptocurrency firms, such as exchanges, advisors and professionals that have either a presence, market product or provide services within the UK market must register with the Financial Conduct Authority.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On 27 June 2021, the financial watchdog demanded that Binance cease all regulated activities in the UK.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In November 2024, the incoming Labour government confirmed that it will proceed with the regulation of cryptoassets and new UK requirements are expected to come into force in 2026.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2021, 17 US states passed laws and resolutions concerning cryptocurrency regulation.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This led the Securities and Exchange Commission to start considering what steps to take.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On 8 July 2021, Senator Elizabeth Warren, part of the Senate Banking Committee, wrote to the chairman of the SEC and demanded answers on cryptocurrency regulation due to the increase in cryptocurrency exchange use and the danger this posed to consumers.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On 5 August 2021, the chairman, Gary Gensler, responded to Warren's letter and called for legislation focused on "crypto trading, lending and DeFi platforms," because of how vulnerable investors could be when they traded on crypto trading platforms without a broker.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] He also argued that many tokens in the crypto market may be unregistered securities without required disclosures or market oversight.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Additionally, Gensler did not hold back in his criticism of stablecoins.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] These tokens, which are pegged to the value of fiat currencies, may allow individuals to bypass important public policy goals related to traditional banking and financial systems, such as anti-money laundering, tax compliance, and sanctions.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On 19 October 2021, the first bitcoin-linked exchange-traded fund (ETF) from ProShares started trading on the NYSE under the ticker "BITO." ProShares CEO Michael L.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Sapir said the ETF would expose bitcoin to a wider range of investors without the hassle of setting up accounts with cryptocurrency providers.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Ian Balina, the CEO of Token Metrics, stated that SEC approval of the ETF was a significant endorsement for the crypto industry because many regulators globally were not in favor of crypto, and retail investors were hesitant to accept crypto.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This event would eventually open more opportunities for new capital and new people in this space.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The Department of the Treasury, on 20 May 2021, announced that it would require any transfer worth $10,000 or more to be reported to the Internal Revenue Service since cryptocurrency already posed a problem where illegal activity like tax evasion was facilitated broadly.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] This release from the IRS was a part of efforts to promote better compliance and consider more severe penalties for tax evaders.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On 17 February 2022, the Department of Justice named Eun Young Choi as the first director of a National Cryptocurrency Enforcement Team to help identify and deal with misuse of cryptocurrencies and other digital assets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The Biden administration faced a dilemma as it tried to develop regulations for the cryptocurrency industry.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On one hand, officials were hesitant to restrict a growing industry.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On the other hand, they were committed to preventing illegal cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] To reconcile these conflicting goals, on 9 March 2022, Biden issued an executive order.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Followed this, on 16 September 2022, the Comprehensive Framework for Responsible Development of Digital Assets document was released to support development of cryptocurrencies and restrict their illegal use.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The executive order included all digital assets, but cryptocurrencies posed both the greatest security risks and potential economic benefits.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] Though this might not address all of the challenges in crypto industry, it was a significant milestone in the US cryptocurrency regulation history.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In February 2023, the SEC ruled that cryptocurrency exchange Kraken's estimated $42 billion in staked assets globally operated as an illegal securities seller.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The company agreed to a $30 million settlement with the SEC and to cease selling its staking service in the US.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The case would impact other major crypto exchanges operating staking programs.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] On 23 March 2023, the SEC issued an alert to investors stating that firms offering crypto asset securities might not be complying with US laws.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] The SEC argued that unregistered offerings of crypto asset securities might not include important information.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p01] In addition the order prohibits the establishment, issuance or promotion of Central bank digital currency and establishes a group tasked with proposing a federal regulatory framework for digital assets within 180 days.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The legal status of cryptocurrencies varies substantially from country to country and is still undefined or changing in many of them.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] At least one study has shown that broad generalizations about the use of bitcoin in illicit finance are significantly overstated and that blockchain analysis is an effective crime fighting and intelligence gathering tool.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] While some countries have explicitly allowed their use and trade, others have banned or restricted it.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] According to the Library of Congress in 2021, an "absolute ban" on trading or using cryptocurrencies applies in 9 countries: Algeria, Bangladesh, Bolivia, China, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Nepal, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In the United States and Canada, state and provincial securities regulators, coordinated through the North American Securities Administrators Association, are investigating "Bitcoin scams" and ICOs in 40 jurisdictions.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Various government agencies, departments, and courts have classified bitcoin differently.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] China Central Bank banned the handling of bitcoins by financial institutions in China in early 2014.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In Russia, though owning cryptocurrency is legal, its residents are only allowed to purchase goods from other residents using the Russian ruble while nonresidents are allowed to use foreign currency.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Regulations and bans that apply to bitcoin probably extend to similar cryptocurrency systems.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In August 2018, the Bank of Thailand announced its plans to create its own cryptocurrency, the Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC).
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In March 2014, the United States Internal Revenue Service (IRS) ruled that bitcoin will be treated as property for tax purposes.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Therefore, virtual currencies are considered commodities subject to capital gains tax.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] As the popularity and demand for cryptocurrencies has increased, so have concerns that they offer an unregulated person-to-person global economy that may become a threat to society.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Concerns abound that they may become tools for anonymous web criminals.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency networks display a lack of regulation that has been criticized as enabling criminals who seek to evade taxes and launder money.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Money laundering issues are also present in regular bank transfers, however with bank-to-bank wire transfers for instance, the account holder must provide a proven identity.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Transactions that occur through the use and exchange of these cryptocurrencies are independent from formal banking systems, and therefore can make tax evasion simpler for individuals.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Since charting taxable income is based upon what a recipient reports to the revenue service, it becomes extremely difficult to account for transactions made using cryptocurrencies, a mode of exchange that is complex and difficult to track.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Systems of anonymity that most cryptocurrencies offer can also serve as a means to launder money.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Rather than laundering money through an intricate network of financial actors and offshore bank accounts, laundering money through cryptocurrencies can be achieved through anonymous transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency makes legal enforcement against extremist groups more complicated, which consequently strengthens them.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] White supremacist Richard Spencer declared bitcoin the "currency of the alt-right".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In February 2014, the world's largest bitcoin exchange, Mt.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Likely due to theft, the company claimed that it had lost nearly 750,000 bitcoins belonging to their clients.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] This added up to approximately 7% of all bitcoins in existence, worth a total of $473 million.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Gox blamed hackers, who had exploited the transaction malleability problems in the network.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The price of a bitcoin fell from a high of about $1,160 in December to under $400 in February.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] On 21 November 2017, Tether announced that it had been hacked, losing $31 million in USDT from its core treasury wallet.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] On 7 December 2017, Slovenian cryptocurrency exchange Nicehash reported that hackers had stolen over $70 million using a hijacked company computer.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] On 19 December 2017, Yapian, the owner of South Korean exchange Youbit, filed for bankruptcy after suffering two hacks that year.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Customers were still granted access to 75% of their assets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In May 2018, Bitcoin Gold had its transactions hijacked and abused by unknown hackers.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Exchanges lost an estimated $18m and bitcoin Gold was delisted from Bittrex after it refused to pay its share of the damages.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] On 13 September 2018, Homero Josh Garza was sentenced to 21 months of imprisonment, followed by three years of supervised release.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Garza had founded the cryptocurrency startups GAW Miners and ZenMiner in 2014, acknowledged in a plea agreement that the companies were part of a pyramid scheme, and pleaded guilty to wire fraud in 2015.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The SEC separately brought a civil enforcement action in the US against Garza, who was eventually ordered to pay a judgment of $9.1 million plus $700,000 in interest.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The SEC's complaint stated that Garza, through his companies, had fraudulently sold "investment contracts representing shares in the profits they claimed would be generated" from mining.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In January 2018, Japanese exchange Coincheck reported that hackers had stolen cryptocurrency worth $530 million.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In June 2018, South Korean exchange Coinrail was hacked, losing over $37 million in crypto.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The hack worsened a cryptocurrency selloff by an additional $42 billion.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] On 9 July 2018, the exchange Bancor, whose code and fundraising had been subjects of controversy, had $23.5 million in crypto stolen.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] A 2020 EU report found that users had lost crypto-assets worth hundreds of millions of US dollars in security breaches at exchanges and storage providers.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Between 2011 and 2019, reported breaches ranged from four to twelve a year.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2019, more than a billion dollars' worth of cryptoassets was reported stolen.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Stolen assets "typically find their way to illegal markets and are used to fund further criminal activity".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] According to the UK 2020 national risk assessment—a comprehensive assessment of money laundering and terrorist financing risk in the UK—the risk of using cryptoassets such as bitcoin for money laundering and terrorism financing is assessed as "medium" (from "low" in the previous 2017 report).
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Legal scholars suggested that the money laundering opportunities may be more perceived than real.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Blockchain analysis company Chainalysis concluded that illicit activities like cybercrime, money laundering and terrorism financing made up only 0.15% of all crypto transactions conducted in 2021, representing a total of $14 billion.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In December 2021, Monkey Kingdom, a NFT project based in Hong Kong, lost US$1.3 million worth of cryptocurrencies via a phishing link used by the hacker.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] On 2 November 2023, Sam Bankman-Fried was pronounced guilty on seven counts of fraud related to FTX.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Federal criminal court sentencing experts speculated on the potential amount of prison time likely to be meted out.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] On 28 March 2024, the court sentenced Bankman-Fried to 25 years in prison.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] According to blockchain data company Chainalysis, criminals laundered $8.6 billion worth of cryptocurrency in 2021, up 30% from the previous year.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The data suggests that rather than managing numerous illicit havens, cybercriminals make use of a small group of purpose-built centralized exchanges for sending and receiving illicit cryptocurrency.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2021, those exchanges received 47% of funds sent by crime-linked addresses.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Almost $2.2 billion worth of cryptocurrencies was embezzled from decentralized finance protocols in 2021, which represents 72% of all cryptocurrency theft in 2021.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Notable businesses include Garantex, Eggchange, Cashbank, Buy-Bitcoin, Tetchange, Bitzlato, and Suex, which was sanctioned by the U.S. in 2021.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitzlato founder and owner Anatoly Legkodymov was arrested following money-laundering charges by the United States Department of Justice.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Dark money has also been flowing into Russia through a dark web marketplace called Hydra, which is powered by cryptocurrency, and enjoyed more than $1 billion in sales in 2020, according to Chainalysis.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The platform demands that sellers liquidate cryptocurrency only through certain regional exchanges, which has made it difficult for investigators to trace the money.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Almost 74% of ransomware revenue in 2021 — over $400 million worth of cryptocurrency — went to software strains likely affiliated with Russia, where oversight is notoriously limited.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, RenBridge—an unregulated alternative to exchanges for transferring value between blockchains—was found to be responsible for the laundering of at least $540 million since 2020.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] It is especially popular with people attempting to launder money from theft.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] This includes a cyberattack on Japanese crypto exchange Liquid that has been linked to North Korea.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Properties of cryptocurrencies gave them popularity in applications such as a safe haven in banking crises and means of payment, which also led to the cryptocurrency use in controversial settings in the form of online black markets, such as Silk Road.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The original Silk Road was shut down in October 2013 and there have been two more versions in use since then.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In the year following the initial shutdown of Silk Road, the number of prominent dark markets increased from four to twelve, while the amount of drug listings increased from 18,000 to 32,000.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Darknet markets present challenges in regard to their legality.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency used in dark markets are not clearly or legally classified in almost all parts of the world.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In the US, bitcoins are regarded as "virtual assets".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] This type of ambiguous classification puts pressure on law enforcement agencies around the world to adapt to the shifting drug trade of dark markets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Various studies have found that crypto-trading is rife with wash trading, a process, illegal in some jurisdictions, involving buyers and sellers being the same person or group, and which may be used to manipulate the price of a cryptocurrency or inflate volume artificially.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Exchanges with higher volumes can demand higher premiums from token issuers.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] A study from 2019 concluded that up to 80% of trades on unregulated cryptocurrency exchanges could be wash trades.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] A 2019 report by Bitwise Asset Management claimed that 95% of all bitcoin trading volume reported on major website CoinMarketCap had been artificially generated, and of 81 exchanges studied, only 10 provided legitimate volume figures.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, cryptocurrencies attracted attention when Western nations imposed severe economic sanctions on Russia in the aftermath of its invasion of Ukraine in February.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] However, American sources warned in March that some crypto-transactions could potentially be used to evade economic sanctions against Russia and Belarus.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In April 2022, the computer programmer Virgil Griffith received a five-year prison sentence in the US for attending a Pyongyang cryptocurrency conference, where he gave a presentation on blockchains which might be used for sanctions evasion.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The Bank for International Settlements summarized several criticisms of cryptocurrencies in Chapter V of their 2018 annual report.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The criticisms include the lack of stability in their price, the high energy consumption, high and variable transactions costs, the poor security and fraud at cryptocurrency exchanges, vulnerability to debasement (from forking), and the influence of miners.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrencies have been compared to Ponzi schemes, pyramid schemes and economic bubbles, such as housing market bubbles.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Regulators in several countries have warned against cryptocurrency and some have taken measures to dissuade users.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] However, research in 2021 by the UK's financial regulator suggests such warnings either went unheard, or were ignored.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Fewer than one in 10 potential cryptocurrency buyers were aware of consumer warnings on the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) website, and 12% of crypto users were not aware that their holdings were not protected by statutory compensation.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Of 1,000 respondents between the ages of eighteen and forty, 70% wrongly assumed cryptocurrencies were regulated, 75% of younger crypto investors claimed to be driven by competition with friends and family, and 58% said that social media enticed them to make high risk investments.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The FCA recommends making use of its warning list, which flags unauthorized financial firms.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Many banks do not offer virtual currency services themselves and can refuse to do business with virtual currency companies.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2014, Gareth Murphy, a senior banking officer, suggested that the widespread adoption of cryptocurrencies may lead to too much money being obfuscated, blinding economists who would use such information to better steer the economy.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] While traditional financial products have strong consumer protections in place, there is no intermediary with the power to limit consumer losses if bitcoins are lost or stolen.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] One of the features cryptocurrency lacks in comparison to credit cards, for example, is consumer protection against fraud, such as chargebacks.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The French regulator Autorité des marchés financiers (AMF) lists 16 websites of companies that solicit investment in cryptocurrency without being authorized to do so in France.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] An October 2021 paper by the National Bureau of Economic Research found that bitcoin suffers from systemic risk as the top 10,000 addresses control about one-third of all bitcoin in circulation.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] It is even worse for miners, with 0.01% controlling 50% of the capacity.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] According to researcher Flipside Crypto, less than 2% of anonymous accounts control 95% of all available bitcoin supply.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] This is considered risky as a great deal of the market is in the hands of a few entities.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] A paper by John Griffin, a finance professor at the University of Texas, and Amin Shams, a graduate student, found that in 2017 the price of bitcoin had been substantially inflated using another cryptocurrency, Tether.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Roger Lowenstein, author of "*Bank of America: The Epic Struggle to Create the Federal Reserve,*" said in a 2022 New York Times story that FTX currency exchange will face over $8 billion in claims.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Non-fungible tokens (NFTs) are digital assets that represent art, collectibles, gaming, etc.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Like crypto, their data is stored on the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] NFTs are bought and traded using cryptocurrency.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The Ethereum blockchain was the first place where NFTs were implemented, but now many other blockchains have created their own versions of NFTs.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] According to Vanessa Grellet, renowned panelist in blockchain conferences, there was an increasing interest from traditional stock exchanges in crypto-assets at the end of the 2010s, while crypto-exchanges such as Coinbase were gradually entering the traditional financial markets.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] This convergence marked a significant trend where conventional financial actors were adopting blockchain technology to enhance operational efficiency, while the crypto world introduced innovations like Security Token Offering (STO), enabling new ways of fundraising.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Tokenization, turning assets such as real estate, investment funds, and private equity into blockchain-based tokens, had the potential to make traditionally illiquid assets more accessible to investors.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Despite the regulatory risks associated with such developments, major financial institutions, including JPMorgan Chase, were actively working on blockchain initiatives, exemplified by the creation of Quorum, a private blockchain platform.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] As the first big Wall Street bank to embrace cryptocurrencies, Morgan Stanley announced on 17 March 2021 that they will be offering access to bitcoin funds for their wealthy clients through three funds which enable bitcoin ownership for investors with an aggressive risk tolerance.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] BNY Mellon on 11 February 2021 announced that it would begin offering cryptocurrency services to its clients.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] On 20 April 2021, Venmo added support to its platform to enable customers to buy, hold and sell cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In October 2021, financial services company Mastercard announced it is working with digital asset manager Bakkt on a platform that would allow any bank or merchant on the Mastercard network to offer cryptocurrency services.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Mining for proof-of-work (PoW) cryptocurrencies requires enormous amounts of electricity and consequently comes with a large carbon footprint due to causing greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Proof-of-work blockchains such as bitcoin, Ethereum, Litecoin, and Monero were estimated to have added between 3 million and 15 million tons of carbon dioxide (CO2) to the atmosphere in the period from 1 January 2016 to 30 June 2017.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] By November 2018, bitcoin was estimated to have an annual energy consumption of 45.8TWh, generating 22.0 to 22.9 million tons of CO2, rivalling nations like Jordan and Sri Lanka.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] By the end of 2021, bitcoin was estimated to produce 65.4 million tons of CO2, as much as Greece, and consume between 91 and 177 terawatt-hours annually.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Critics have also identified a large electronic waste problem in disposing of mining rigs.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Mining hardware is improving at a fast rate, quickly resulting in older generations of hardware.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitcoin is the least energy-efficient cryptocurrency, using 707.6 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Before June 2021, China was the primary location for bitcoin mining.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] However, due to concerns over power usage and other factors, China forced out bitcoin operations, at least temporarily.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] As a result, the United States promptly emerged as the top global leader in the industry.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] An example of a gross amount of electronic waste associated with bitcoin mining operations in the US is a facility located in Dalton, Georgia which is consuming nearly the same amount of electricity as the combined power usage of 97,000 households in its vicinity.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Another example is that Riot Platforms operates a bitcoin mining facility in Rockdale, Texas, which consumes approximately as much electricity as the nearby 300,000 households.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] This makes it the most energy-intensive bitcoin mining operation in the United States.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The world's second-largest cryptocurrency, Ethereum, uses 62.56 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] XRP is the world's most energy efficient cryptocurrency, using 0.0079 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Although the biggest PoW blockchains consume energy on the scale of medium-sized countries, the annual power demand from proof-of-stake (PoS) blockchains is on a scale equivalent to a housing estate.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] *The Times* identified six "environmentally friendly" cryptocurrencies: Bitgreen, Cardano, Chia, IOTA, Nano, and Solarcoin.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Academics and researchers have used various methods for estimating the energy use and energy efficiency of blockchains.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] This equates to Polkadot consuming 7 times the electricity of an average U.S. home, Cardano 57 homes and Solana 200 times as much.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The research concluded that PoS networks consumed 0.001% the electricity of the bitcoin network.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] University College London researchers reached a similar conclusion.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Variable renewable energy power stations could invest in bitcoin mining to reduce curtailment, hedge electricity price risk, stabilize the grid, increase the profitability of renewable energy power stations and therefore accelerate transition to sustainable energy.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] There are also purely technical elements in play.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] For example, technological advancement in cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin result in high up-front costs to miners in the form of specialized hardware and software.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency transactions are normally irreversible after a number of blocks confirm the transaction.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Additionally, cryptocurrency private keys can be permanently lost from local storage due to malware, data loss, or simply carelessness.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] This precludes the cryptocurrency from any usage whatsoever, permanently, thus removing it from the market.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In September 2015, the establishment of the peer-reviewed academic journal *Ledger* (ISSN 2379-5980) was announced.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] It covers studies of cryptocurrencies and related technologies, and is published by the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which will then be timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address in the first page of their papers.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] A number of aid agencies have started accepting donations in cryptocurrencies, including UNICEF.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Christopher Fabian, principal adviser at UNICEF Innovation, said the children's fund would uphold donor protocols, meaning that people making donations online would have to pass checks before they were allowed to deposit funds.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] However, in 2021, there was a backlash against donations in bitcoin because of the environmental emissions it caused.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Some agencies stopped accepting bitcoin and others turned to "greener" cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The U.S. arm of Greenpeace stopped accepting bitcoin donations after seven years.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, the Ukrainian government raised over US$10,000,000 worth of aid through cryptocurrency following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitcoin was characterized as a speculative bubble in 2014–2018 by eight winners of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences: Angus Deaton, Oliver Hart, James Heckman, Paul Krugman, Thomas Sargent, Robert J.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Shiller, Joseph Stiglitz, and Richard Thaler; and in 2013–2018 by central bank officials including Agustín Carstens (Mexico), Vítor Constâncio (Portugal), Alan Greenspan (US), and Nout Wellink (Netherlands).
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Investors Warren Buffett and George Soros have respectively characterized it in 2014–2018 as a "mirage" and a "bubble".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Business executives Jack Ma and JP Morgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon have called it in 2017–2018 a "bubble" and a "fraud", respectively, although Jamie Dimon later said in 2018 that he regretted stating bitcoin was a fraud.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Fink in 2017 called bitcoin an "index of money laundering".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In June 2022, business magnate Bill Gates said that cryptocurrencies are "100% based on greater fool theory".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Legal scholars criticize the lack of regulation, which hinders conflict resolution when crypto assets are at the center of a legal dispute, for example a divorce or an inheritance.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In Switzerland, jurists generally deny that cryptocurrencies are objects that fall under property law, as cryptocurrencies do not belong to any class of legally defined objects (*Typenzwang*, the legal numerus clausus).
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Therefore, it is debated whether anybody could even be sued for embezzlement of cryptocurrency if they had access to someone's wallet.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] However, in the law of obligations and contract law, any kind of object would be legally valid, but the object would have to be tied to an identified counterparty.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] However, inasmuch the more popular cryptocurrencies can be freely and quickly exchanged into legal tender, they are financial assets and have to be taxed and accounted for as such.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] Losses associated with cryptocurrency investments have been linked to suicides.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2018, an increase in crypto-related suicides was noticed after the cryptocurrency market crashed in August.
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The situation was particularly critical in Korea as crypto traders were on "suicide watch".
[src:cosmos-network/cryptocurrency-p02] The May 2022 collapse of the Luna currency operated by Terra also led to reports of suicidal investors in crypto-related subreddits.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] For a blockchain transaction to be recognized, it must be appended to the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] In a proof-of-stake blockchain, the appending entities are named *minters* or **validators** (in proof-of-work blockchains, this task is carried out by the miners); in most protocols, the validators receive a reward for doing so.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] For the blockchain to remain secure, it must have a mechanism to prevent a malicious user or group from taking over a majority of validation.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] PoS accomplishes this by requiring that validators have some quantity of blockchain tokens, requiring potential attackers to acquire a large fraction of the tokens on the blockchain to mount an attack.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Proof-of-work (PoW), another commonly used consensus mechanism, uses a validation of computational prowess to verify transactions, requiring a potential attacker to acquire a large fraction of the computational power of the validator network.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] This incentivizes consuming huge quantities of energy.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Riposo and Gupta showed that a formal PoS mathematical model can derive a metric for the expected gain of a staker.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] They introduced a forward-method model that computes staking rewards as the staking return per block-validation period and proved that the resulting interest equals the ratio of the average staking gain to the total staked coins.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The model incorporates PoS-specific factors such as slashing (penalties for misbehavior) and Maximal Extractable Value (MEV), showing that slashing reduces expected rewards and that MEV links transaction-fee extraction to the average staking gain.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] In addition, the authors illustrated the model using Ethereum 2.0, and presented an analogous derivation for PoW consensus.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Early PoS implementations were plagued by a number of new attacks that exploited the unique vulnerabilities of the PoS protocols.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Eventually, two dominant designs emerged: *Byzantine-fault-tolerance-based* and *chain-based* approaches.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The additional vulnerabilities of PoS schemes are directly related to their advantage: a relatively low amount of calculations required when constructing a blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The low amount of computing power involved allows a class of attacks that replace a non-negligible portion of the main blockchain with a hijacked version.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] These attacks are called in literature by different names, including *Long-Range*, *Alternative History*, *Alternate History*, and *History Revision*, and are unfeasible in the PoW schemes due to the sheer volume of calculations required.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The early stages of a blockchain are much more malleable for rewriting, as they likely have much smaller group of stakeholders involved, simplifying the collusion.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] If the per-block and per-transaction rewards are offered, then the malicious group can, for example, redo the entire history and collect these rewards.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The classic "Short-Range" attack (bribery attack) that rewrites just a small tail portion of the chain is also possible.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The PoS schemes enable low-cost creation of blockchain alternatives starting at any point in history (*costless simulation*); submitting these forks to eager validators endangers the stability of the system.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] If this situation persists, it can allow double-spending, where a digital token can be spent more than once.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] This can be mitigated through penalizing validators who validate conflicting chains ("economic finality") or by structuring the rewards so that there is no economic incentive to create conflicts.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Byzantine-fault-tolerance-based PoS are generally considered robust against this threat (see below).
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The smaller amount of calculations required for solving the puzzle for high-value stakeholders helps to avoid excessive hardware.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Also known as "committee-based", this scheme involves an election of a committee of validators using a verifiable random function with probabilities of being elected higher with higher stake.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Validators then randomly take turns producing blocks.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] NPoS is utilized by Ouroboros Praos and BABE.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The BFT consensus is used to finalize the most-voted block.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The scheme works as long as no more than a third of validators are dishonest.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] BFT schemes are used in Tendermint and Casper FFG.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Proof of stake delegated systems use a two-stage process: first, the stakeholders elect a validation committee, a.k.a.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] *witnesses*, by voting proportionally to their stakes, then the witnesses take turns in a round-robin fashion to propose new blocks that are then voted upon by the witnesses, usually in the BFT-like fashion.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Since there are fewer validators in the DPoS than in many other PoS schemes, the consensus can be established faster.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The scheme is used in many chains, including EOS, Lisk, Tron.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] In the liquid PoS anyone with a stake can declare themselves a validator, but for the small holders it makes sense to delegate their voting rights instead to larger players in exchange for some benefits (like periodic payouts).
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] A market is established where the validators compete on the fees, reputation, and other factors.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Token holders are free to switch their support to another validator at any time.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The exact definition of "stake" varies from implementation to implementation.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] For instance, some cryptocurrencies use the concept of "coin age", the product of the number of tokens with the amount of time that a single user has held them, rather than merely the number of tokens, to define a validator's stake.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The first functioning implementation of a proof-of-stake cryptocurrency was Peercoin, introduced in 2012.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Other cryptocurrencies, such as Blackcoin, Nxt, Cardano, and Algorand followed.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] However, as of 2017, PoS cryptocurrencies were still not as widely used as proof-of-work cryptocurrencies.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] In September 2022, Ethereum, the second-largest cryptocurrency, switched from PoW to a PoS consensus mechanism, after several proposals and some delays.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] US regulators have argued over the legal status of the proof-of-stake model, with the Securities and Exchange Commission claiming that staking rewards are the equivalent of interest, so coins such as ether and ada are financial securities.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] However, in 2024, the SEC sidestepped the question by recognising Ethereum market funds on condition that they did not stake their coins.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] The level of staking of ether at 27% of total supply was low compared with Cardano (66%) and Solana (63%).
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] However, not staking their tokens meant that the funds were losing about 3% of potential returns a year.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] In January 2022, Erik Thedéen, the vice-chair of the European Securities and Markets Authority, called on the EU to ban the PoW model in favor of PoS because of the latter's lower energy consumption.
[src:cosmos-network/proof-of-stake] Ethereum's switch to proof-of-stake was estimated to have cut its energy use by over 99%.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:cosmos-network/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
